	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>No. 46 South Street</placeName></p>
				<p>Mr dear <addressee>Mr Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I was very glad to see<lb/> your <sic>autography</sic> again and <add>&#63;</add> your<lb/> note of <date>7</date> inst with great pleasure as I<lb/> now welcome you home again. I am<lb/> also very glad that you return in improved<lb/> health and that your <sic>visitings</sic> have not<lb/> proved unsuccessful pecuniarily</p>
				<p>I intended to write to our mutual and<lb/> good friend <persName>Mr. Cozens</persName> during your<lb/> absence and am heartily sorry that<lb/> I did not&#44; but somehow time slips by<lb/> so rapidly that it comes and goes before<lb/> I am aware of it. However I hope to do bet&#45;<lb/>ter next time. My health has bee un&#45;<lb/>commonly good during the winter and<lb/> is so now but I fear for the next few<lb/> months&#44; particularly as I am so situated<lb/> that I do not see how I can get away<lb/> from home. I had such a delightful</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>visit down <placeName>South</placeName>&#44; especially in <placeName>Mobile</placeName><lb/> last spring&#44; that I should much like<lb/> to repeat it. You do not say a word about<lb/> our <placeName>Mobile</placeName> friends nor have I heard a single<lb/> word from them since my return although<lb/> I have written <persName>Dr. Wolff</persName> twice and have<lb/> sent several verbal messages to him and<lb/> to his interesting family. I hope they<lb/> are in good health and spirits&#44; although<lb/> I can hardly expect the latter <add>&#63;</add> they<lb/> something more than humor.  The<lb/> heathen Bloodhounds at <placeName>Washington</placeName><lb/> seem determined crush and beggar the<lb/> entire <placeName>south</placeName> and her proper<add>&#63;</add>.  I earnestly<lb/> pray that some power may yet frustrate<lb/> their informal plans.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Your monthly Parcels have been regularly<lb/> received and distributed the Occident for<lb/> your <placeName>New York</placeName> subscribers sent to me whilst<lb/> you <sic>was</sic> away I distributed though the P.O.<lb/> Your last parcel by <persName>Adams &#38; Co</persName> was marked<lb/> paid by you&#44; but they insisted on collecting<lb/> the freight from me to the extent of 30&#162;</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>and the 2 previous parcels each 50&#162;.  If<lb/> you prepaid them you have a claim<lb/> upon the compy for the amount</p>
				<p>I noticed&#44; with much regret in the newspapers<lb/> of last week the death of <persName>Mr. Cozens</persName><lb/> valued friend <persName>Dr. Hewitt</persName> of <placeName>Budapest</placeName><lb/> I am sure it was a sad blow to her</p>
				<p>I noticed in the last No. of the Occident<lb/> that you were again the <add>&#63;</add> of one of<lb/> your good people&#44; it must be very<lb/> gratifying to you to be thus remembered<lb/> and I sincerely hope you will continue<lb/> so to be.</p>
				<p>Please remember me affectionately to<lb/> <persName>Mrs Cozens</persName> and to <persName>Miss Ella</persName> and believe<lb/> as ever&#44; in great haste.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Your sincere friend</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)"><persName role="author">Hanford</persName></p>
				<p>PS. as yet I have no collections to report<lb/> but have some in train</p>
		</body>
